{{refimprove|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox COA case |Litigants=Estate of Rockefeller v. Commissioner |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=April 22, |ArgueYear=1985 |DecideDate=May 24, |DecideYear=1985 |FullName=Estate of Nelson A. Rockefeller, Deceased, [[Laurance S. Rockefeller]], [[J. Richardson Dilworth]] and Donal C. O'Brien, Jr., Executors and Margaretta F. Rockefeller v. Commissioner of Internal Revenue |Citations=762 [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/762/264/406661/ 264]; 56 A.F.T.R.2d 85-5094; 53 USLW 2620; 85-1 USTC ([[CCH (company)|CCH]]) ¶ 9429 |Prior=83 [[United States Tax Court|T.C.]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/198445183xtc3681428 368] (1984) |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[Wilfred Feinberg]], [[Henry Friendly]], [[Jon O. Newman]] |Majority=Friendly |JoinMajority=Feinberg, Newman |LawsApplied=[[Internal Revenue Code]] [[Internal Revenue Code section 162(a)|§ 162(a)]] |keywords= {{hlist |[[Business expense]]}} }} '''Estate of Rockefeller v. Commissioner''', 762 [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] 264 (2d Cir. 1985),<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Estate of Rockefeller v. Commissioner |vol=762 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=264 |pinpoint= |court=2d Cir. |date=1985 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/762/264/406661/ |accessdate=2017-11-27 |quote=}}</ref> was a case in which the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] held that [[Internal Revenue Code section 162(a)|section 162(a)]] of the [[Internal Revenue Code]] only allows deductions against income for expenses that occur while carrying on a trade or business.
==Facts of the case== [[Nelson Rockefeller]] had incurred $550,159.78 worth of legal fees and services with regard to his 1974 vice presidential confirmation hearings. Mr. Rockefeller then claimed a $63,275 deduction on his 1974 [[Tax return (United States)|income tax return]], which was the amount of his salary as vice-president.
==Determination of the court== The 2nd Circuit affirmed the Tax Courts ruling that the deductions were not allowed under IRC section 162.<ref>{{USC|26|162}}</ref> The Court essentially compared Rockefeller’s past job as [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]] with his position as [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] and found that the two positions did not constitute the same trade or business. Mr. Rockefeller’s estate argued that his trade or business was that of public service, but there was no authority that supported such a broad interpretation. Thus, the legal and consulting fees were not incurred in carrying out a trade or business, but in anticipation of doing so. Essentially, the court ruled that the expenses could not be deducted because Rockefeller was not yet “carrying on” the business of being Vice President.
