{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Planned Parenthood v. Rounds |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |SubmitDate=January 9, |SubmitYear=2012 |DecideDate=July 24, |DecideYear=2012 |FullName=Planned Parenthood Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota; Carol E. Ball, M.D. v. [[Mike Rounds]], Governor; [[Marty J. Jackley]], Attorney General, in their official capacities, et al. |Citations=686 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120724142 889] |Prior=Preliminary injunction granted, 375 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20051256375fsupp2d88111172 881] ([[United States District Court for the District of South Dakota|D.S.D.]] 2005); injunction vacated, remanded, 530 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081254530f3d72411181 724] (8th Cir. 2008); summary judgment granted in part, denied in part, 650 [[F. Supp. 2d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infdco20100208442 972] (D.S.D. 2009); affirmed in part, reversed in part, 653 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20110902084 662] (8th Cir. 2011); rehearing ''[[en banc]]'' granted, 662 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/inadvfco120206000119 1072] (8th Cir. 2011) |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[William J. Riley]], [[Roger Leland Wollman]], [[James B. Loken]], [[Diana E. Murphy]], [[Kermit Edward Bye]], [[Michael Joseph Melloy]], [[Lavenski Smith]], [[Steven Colloton]], [[Raymond Gruender]], [[William Duane Benton]], [[Bobby Shepherd]] (''en banc'') |Majority=Gruender |JoinMajority=Riley, Loken, Smith, Benton, Shepherd |Concurrence=Loken |Concurrence/Dissent=Colloton |Dissent=Murphy |JoinDissent=Wollman, Bye, Melloy |LawsApplied=[[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amends. I]]; [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|XIV]] }} '''''[[Planned Parenthood]] v. Rounds''''', 686 F.3d 889 (8th Cir. 2012) (en banc),<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Planned Parenthood v. Rounds |vol=686 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=889 |pinpoint= |court=[[8th Cir.]] |date=2012 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20120724142 |accessdate=2018-07-11 |quote=}} {{Include-FedCourts}}</ref> was a decision by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit]] that upheld a provision of a South Dakota law that requires a doctor to inform a patient, prior to providing an abortion, that one of the "known medical risks of the procedure and statistically significant risk factors" is an "increased risk of suicide ideation and suicide."<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Planned Parenthood v. Rounds |vol=375 |reporter=F. Supp. 2d |opinion=881 |pinpoint=884 |court=[[United States District Court for the District of South Dakota|D.S.D.]] |date=2005 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/20051256375fsupp2d88111172 |accessdate=2018-07-11 |quote=}}</ref>
The district court, in setting the initial injunction against enforcing this law, relied on studies that showed some correlation between abortion and suicide, but showed no evidence that an abortion causes a woman to be at greater risk for suicide. Rather, the studies indicated that the same factors that cause a woman to seek an abortion, like emotional distress, domestic violence and socioeconomic disadvantage, also make them more likely to be depressed and suicidal. [[Abortion and mental health|The scientific consensus is that abortion does not increase the risk of any mental health problems]].
The Eighth Circuit noted that states may mandate disclosures as part of obtaining informed consent, so long as those disclosures are neither false nor misleading. The Eighth Circuit acknowledged that the record did not support an inference that abortion causes suicide. However, the court said that the South Dakota law does not require doctors to inform women that abortion causes suicide; it requires only that women hear that abortion is associated with an increased risk of suicide, and as used in its scientific sense, "association" does not imply causation.
