==Production==
In December 2010 Hagen approached actress Mercedes Rose with the idea to create a paranormal web-based show, as he noted that the word "ghost" was a common search term.<ref name=WW /> Rose later described the idea as "''[[Gilmore Girls]]'' meets ''[[Paranormal Activity]]'' with a little ''[[Easy A]]'' thrown in."<ref name="showfax1">{{cite web|author=|url=http://more.showfax.com/plus/pov/2011/09/actors_are_liars.html |title=Actors Are Liars (The Actors Voice - POV) |publisher=More.showfax.com |date=2011-09-15 |accessdate=2012-08-16}}</ref> The show would be unscripted and center around a "girl trying to prove her house is haunted".<ref name="showfax1" /> Hagen and Rose then enlisted Rose's daughter, Kat McKenzie, to star as the series's main character.<ref name=Bustle>{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Caitlin|title='The Haunting of Sunshine Girl' Creator Paige McKenzie Talks Her Unexpected Biggest Fear And All Things Spooky|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/71368-the-haunting-of-sunshine-girl-creator-paige-mckenzie-talks-her-unexpected-biggest-fear-and-all-things|publisher=Bustle|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> From there the three worked on the series's concept and chose to develop the story as the series progressed, as they "wanted something that we could keep doing on YouTube but could also be expanded into a bigger "universe" with these paranormal rules and characters we’ve set up."<ref name=NewMediaRockstars>{{cite web|last1=Klima|first1=Jeff|title='The Haunting of Sunshine Girl’s’ Paige McKenzie Talks Her YouTube Series and New Major Book/Movie Deal [INTERVIEW]|url=http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/05/the-haunting-of-sunshine-girls-paige-mckenzie-talks-her-youtube-series-and-new-major-bookmovie-deal-interview/|publisher=[[NewMediaRockstars]]|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> McKenzie chose to base the character upon herself, as she felt that the channel "wouldn’t feel genuine if it felt like I was putting on some sort of act."<ref name=NewMediaRockstars /> McKenzie did not initially reveal her name to viewers until 2013, a move that she later stated was due to fear of stalkers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Samotin|first1=Perrie|title=The Haunting of Sunshine Girl: The YouTube Series About to be the Next YA Hit|url=http://stylecaster.com/the-haunting-of-sunshine-girl-the-youtube-series-about-to-be-the-next-ya-hit/|publisher=StyleCaster|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>

Most episodes are filmed with a flip camera by the actors themselves. This filming format was chosen as it would allow them to film multiple episodes at a time, which would make it easier to post new videos each week. Hagen noted that he had to use specific keywords that would allow for the best [[search-engine optimization]], which made it easier for users to find and enable them to have "100,000 views within weeks" without having to actively promote the channel.<ref name=WW /> Aside from optimization, McKenzie found that interacting with fans also raised the series's visibility and viewership numbers. Fans can interact with McKenzie via her social media accounts and by sharing videos.<ref name=WW /> The channel became a [[YouTube Partner]] in 2011 and during 2014 made $4,000 to $6,000 a month via ads.<ref name=WW />

In 2013 McKenzie took part in a scholarship competition in ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'' magazine, where she ran under her real name and mentioned ''The Haunting of Sunshine Girl''.<ref>{{cite web|title=MEET THE PRETTY AMAZING FINALISTS!|url=http://www.seventeen.com/life/g369/2013-pretty-amazing-finalists/?slide=2|publisher=Seventeen|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> This contest attracted the attention of a literary agent, who helped finalize a deal with the [[Weinstein Company]] to produce a book and television series based on ''The Haunting of Sunshine Girl''.<ref name=WW />

==Spin-Offs==

===Sunshine's World===
Sunshine's World is another YouTube channel by Coat Tale Productions. There is no plot. Sunshine Girl just posts videos about her visiting a pumpkin farm, a shop in Portland or showing her posters to the audience. It is the [[vlog]] of an 18-year-old girl. The last upload to this channel was March 9, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/user/SunshinesVlog|title = Sunshine's Vlog YouTube Channel|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

===Sunshine Screen Prints===
In "Sunshine Screen Prints," Sunshine Girl shows her audience the basics of [[screen printing]].

===Uncle Tommy's YouTube Confessions===
''Uncle Tommy's YouTube Confessions'' is the first spin-off based on a supporting character of "The Haunting of Sunshine Girl". It is an interactive series in which the audience sends secret confessions via comment or email to "Uncle Tommy," which he and friends might then read on the show.  Occasionally Kat or Sunshine Girl appear in Uncle Tommy's videos.

==Feature films==

=== ''Sunshine Girl and the Hunt for Black Eyed Kids'' ===
In November 2011 Coat Tale Productions launched a [[Kickstarter]] project to fund a feature film, ''In Search of Black Eyed Kids'' (later retitled ''Sunshine Girl and the Hunt for Black Eyed Kids'').<ref>{{cite web|title=An Unknown Horror: In Search of Black Eyed Kids (Feature)|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1592594525/an-unknown-horror-in-search-of-black-eyed-kids-fea?lang=en|publisher=Kickstarter|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The film would follow Sunshine and other series characters as they search for [[black-eyed children]], an [[urban legend]] surrounding supernatural creatures. The Kickstarter campaign met its goals, but Mercedes Rose later stated that the majority of the funding came from friends, family, and members of their film community.<ref name="Kickstarter BEK">{{cite web|last1=Rose |first1=Mercedes |title=I Hate Roller Coasters (Or, The Highs and Lows of Crowd Funding) |url=http://unscripted.backstage.com/2011/12/i-hate-roller-coasters-or-the-highs-and-lows-of-crowd-funding.html |publisher=Backstage (archived) |accessdate=26 September 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426014125/http://unscripted.backstage.com/2011/12/i-hate-roller-coasters-or-the-highs-and-lows-of-crowd-funding.html |archivedate=April 26, 2012 }}</ref>

Filming for ''Sunshine Girl and the Hunt for Black Eyed Kids'' began in January 2012 in Portland, Oregon, and was produced in association with [[Lyon Films]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman |first=Zachary |url=http://www.columbian.com/news/2012/jan/10/in-search-of-black-eyed-kids/ |title=‘Black Eyed Kids’ sought for movie |publisher=The Columbian |date=2012-01-10 |accessdate=2012-08-16}}</ref> The movie was released on DVD in December 2012 and is available via download.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunshine Girl and the Hunt for Black Eyed Kids (review)|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/dvd-reviews/sunshine-girl-and-the-hunt-for-black-eyed-kids|publisher=JoBlo.com|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>

=== THR33 ===
In November 2013 McKenzie launched an [[Indiegogo]] project to fund a second feature film, then temporarily titled ''Alone'', and the campaign raised [[USD|$]]2,480.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alone - Feature Film Pre-Order - *Temporary Title|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/alone-feature-film-pre-order-temporary-title#/story|publisher=IndieGoGo|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The film is set during the 1980s and centers around a girl (played by McKenzie) stuck in a cabin with a ghost.<ref>{{cite web|title=YouTube star Paige McKenzie to star in horror film "Thr33"|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/2015/02/12/youtube-star-paige-mckenzie-to-star-in-horror-film-thr33-2685870?lt_source=external,manual|publisher=MoviePilot|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The film's name was later changed to ''Three'' (also stylized as ''Thr33'') and filming commenced in 2014.<ref name=WW>{{cite web|last1=JACOBSON|first1=REBECCA|title=80 Million Paige Views|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-22863-80-million-paige-views.html|publisher=Wiliamette Week|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> Thr33 was released on 29 January 2016.

==Books==
In 2014 the Weinstein Co. announced that they had closed a multiplatform deal to adapt ''The Haunting of Sunshine Girl'' into a [[young adult novel]] and film franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weinstein-adapting-haunting-sunshine-girl-701365 |title=Weinstein Co. Adapting 'Haunting of Sunshine Girl' Web Series Into Book, Film Franchise (Exclusive) |publisher=The Hollywood Reported |date=2014-05-08 |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> On March 24, 2015 ''The Haunting of Sunshine Girl'' was released in hardback, e-book, and audiobook via [[Weinstein Books]], and follows the same plot as the web series's first story arc.<ref name=nytbook>{{cite web|last1=Alter|first1=Alexander|title=YouTube’s ‘Sunshine Girl’ Comes to Print|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/25/business/media/youtubes-sunshine-girl-comes-to-print.html?_r=0|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> Critical reception for the book was mixed, with some outlets criticizing the work for being too similar to other supernatural young adult novels while others praised it for its character interactions and chills.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grossman|first1=Lev|title=Review: Little Miss Sunshine Girl|url=http://time.com/3750532/sunshine-girl-review/|publisher=Time|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Paige McKenzie, The Haunting of Sunshine Girl|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-24301-paige_mckenzie_the_haunting_of_sunshine_girl.html|publisher=Williamette Week|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Haunting of Sunshine Girl, Book 1 (review)|url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/book-reviews/the-haunting-of-sunshine-girl-book-1|publisher=[[Commonsensemedia]]|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chopin|first1=Allison|title=‘The Haunting of Sunshine Girl’ is chilling ghost story based on YouTube series: review|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/pageviews/haunting-sunshine-girl-chilling-ghost-story-blog-entry-1.2156238|publisher=New York Daily News|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>

On March 1, 2016 the sequel to The ''Haunting of Sunshine Girl'' was released titled ''The Awakening of Sunshine Girl''  in hardback, e-book, and audiobook via [[Weinstein Books]], and like its predecessor had many praises for the scary plot and deep character development and criticism for the lack originality based on other supernatural young adult novels.

The third and final book, "The Sacrifice of Sunshine girl", was released April 4, 2017. The book completed the trilogy and was also based on the hit YouTube channel.

==TV show==
In March 2015 McKenzie announced that there were plans for the Weinstein Co. to adapt ''The Haunting of Sunshine Girl'' into either a feature film or television show, along with a novel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marshall|first1=Cory|title=Behind the scenes: "The Haunting of Sunshine Girl"|url=http://www.katu.com/news/local/Behind-the-scenes-The-Haunting-of-Sunshine-Girl-296380171.html|publisher=KATU|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The following month McKenzie issued a [[press release]] stating that it had been decided that they would progress with a television show rather than a film, as they felt that "TV would be an easier transition."<ref name=PR>{{cite web|title=The Haunting of Sunshine Girl's Paige McKenzie Talks Book Adaptation and Reveals It Will Now Be Adapted Into a TV Show Instead of a Movie|url=http://www.prweb.com/releases/2015/04/prweb12668600.htm|publisher=PR Web (press release)|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> The series will be based on the novel released in September 2015 and will have McKenzie in the starring role.<ref name=nytbook />

